## Redeploy dev (target dev-lakebase): refresh Lakebase database resource ID after recreating ontobricks-test

Context: the user requested a dev redeploy. The first `make deploy` (target
`dev-lakebase`) failed because the Lakebase project `ontobricks-test`
referenced in `databricks.yml` had been deleted, so terraform could not
create the `mcp_ontobricks_app` postgres resource binding (`branches/
production does not exist`). After the user recreated the project, a
second deploy then failed with two follow-up errors: (1) the existing
`mcp-ontobricks` app was unmanaged by this bundle's terraform state,
(2) the registry volume `benoit_cayla.ontobricks_deployed_test.
registry_test` did not exist in Unity Catalog. Fixed all three, both
apps are now `RUNNING` and `/healthz` returns 200.

Changes:

1. `databricks.yml` — bumped the default `lakebase_database_resource`
   variable from the deleted `db-tvs3-r0yrbvtunp` to the new
   `db-1vw1-34ir9n3vrn` of the recreated `ontobricks-test` project
   (database `databricks_postgres`, branch `production`). Branch path
   was unchanged.

2. Bundle bind (one-shot, no source change) — bound the existing
   `mcp-ontobricks` app to this bundle's terraform state via
   `databricks bundle deployment bind mcp_ontobricks_app mcp-ontobricks
   -t dev-lakebase --auto-approve`. Equivalent to running
   `scripts/deploy.sh --bind` for the MCP app, which the script does
   not currently cover (it only binds `ontobricks_dev_app`).

3. Unity Catalog volume (one-shot, no source change) — created the
   missing `benoit_cayla.ontobricks_deployed_test.registry_test`
   MANAGED volume that the dev app's `WRITE_VOLUME` resource expects.

4. `make deploy` (target `dev-lakebase`) succeeded:
   - `ontobricks-dev` → RUNNING, https://ontobricks-dev-2508734981122804.aws.databricksapps.com (`/healthz` → 200)
   - `mcp-ontobricks` → RUNNING, https://mcp-ontobricks-2508734981122804.aws.databricksapps.com (refreshed via `bundle run mcp_ontobricks_app -t dev-lakebase`)
   - App self-permissions bootstrap: ✓ `CAN_MANAGE` granted to ontobricks-dev SP.
   - Lakebase schema permissions bootstrap: skipped — the
     `ontobricks_registry` schema does not yet exist in
     `databricks_postgres`. Expected on a freshly recreated project;
     re-run `scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh -a ontobricks-dev`
     after initialising the registry from Settings > Registry >
     Initialize.

Modified files:
- `databricks.yml`

Tests: `uv run pytest -q` → **1892 passed** in 62.4s (run pre-deploy
per the deploy skill's pre-flight gate; no source code changed in this
deploy beyond the bundle config above, so tests were not re-run after
the deploy).

Follow-ups for the user:
- Open the OntoBricks app → **Settings > Registry > Initialize** to
  create the `ontobricks_registry` schema in Lakebase.
- Then re-run `scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh -a ontobricks-dev`
  to grant USAGE/DML/sequence privileges to the app's service
  principal.
- Confirm the `sql-warehouse` and `volume` resource bindings in
  **Compute > Apps > ontobricks-dev > Resources** (DAB cannot bind
  these — must be done in the UI per README.md).

## Cockpit: "Active Version" now reflects the MCP-enabled version

Context: with V1 toggled as the API/MCP-active version and V2 loaded
in-session, the Cockpit's "Active Version" tile incorrectly displayed
v2. Root cause was in `Domain.get_version_status`, which returned
`is_active = is_latest` and the front-end then rendered
`available_versions[0]` (the latest version) on the tile. This
conflated two semantically distinct concepts: "loaded version is the
latest" (used by `version-check.js` to gate the read-only body class
that hides write-controls + the wizard sidebar) versus "version
exposed via API/MCP" (what the Cockpit tile is meant to advertise).

Changes:

1. `src/back/objects/domain/Domain.py` — `Domain.get_version_status`
   now also calls `RegistryService.find_mcp_version(folder)` and
   returns the result as a new `active_version` field. `is_active`
   keeps its legacy meaning (`is_latest`) so the read-only body class
   in `version-check.js` and all its CSS gates (incl. the
   `view-mode-hidden` wizard link) continue to behave correctly.

2. `src/front/static/domain/js/domain-validation.js` —
   `updateVersionTiles` now renders the Active Version tile from
   `vs.active_version` (falling back to "None" when no version is
   MCP-enabled). The "(not loaded)" suffix appears when the loaded
   version differs from the MCP-active one.

Modified files:
- `src/back/objects/domain/Domain.py`
- `src/front/static/domain/js/domain-validation.js`

Tests: `uv run pytest -q` → **1892 passed** in 57.7s. (First run
showed 3 spurious e2e failures from a transient mid-edit state where
`is_active` had been broadened beyond `is_latest` and the wizard
sidebar was therefore hidden by the read-only-version body class;
fixed before commit.)

## Silence GitGuardian "Generic Database Assignment" false positive
in Lakebase auth tests

Context: GitGuardian alert **32279171** (commit `a3b55be`) flagged the
`autoscaling_pg_env` fixture in `tests/test_lakebase_auth.py` as a
"Generic Database Assignment" — the realistic-looking Lakebase
hostname (`ep-damp-art-d1l8gclo.…`) plus a UUID-shaped `PGUSER` set
together as `PGHOST` / `PGPORT` / `PGDATABASE` / `PGUSER` was enough
to fingerprint it as a credential block, even though every value was
synthetic test data. `tests/test_settings_lakebase_tier.py` reused
the same hostname and was affected by the same shape.

Changes:

1. `tests/test_lakebase_auth.py` — extracted the synthetic Lakebase
   values to module-level constants (`_FAKE_PGHOST`, `_FAKE_PGHOST_RO`,
   `_FAKE_PGUSER`, `_FAKE_PROJECT_ID`, `_FAKE_PG_TOKEN`) with a header
   comment that explicitly calls out their fixture-only role and
   references the GitGuardian alert ID. Renamed the host slug from
   `ep-damp-art-d1l8gclo` → `ep-test-fake1234` so it cannot be
   mistaken for a real endpoint, and switched the all-zero UUID for
   `PGUSER`. Every line that the scanners had been matching now
   carries both `# pragma: allowlist secret` (detect-secrets) and
   `# ggignore` (ggshield) markers.

2. `tests/test_settings_lakebase_tier.py` — same hostname rename
   (`ep-damp-art-d1l8gclo` → `ep-test-fake1234`) on the `HOST` /
   `RO_HOST` class constants, with the same dual-pragma markers.

Modified files:
- `tests/test_lakebase_auth.py`
- `tests/test_settings_lakebase_tier.py`

Tests: `uv run pytest -q` → **1892 passed** in 68.1s. Touched tests
also re-run in isolation (`tests/test_lakebase_auth.py
tests/test_settings_lakebase_tier.py` → 20 passed).

Follow-up for the user: dismiss GitGuardian alert **32279171** as a
false positive. Future scans on the renamed values + inline pragmas
should not re-trigger.

## Patch GitPython transitive vuln (GHSA-rpm5-65cw-6hj4 / SNYK-PYTHON-GITPYTHON-16298057)

Context: SCA scan flagged GitPython 3.1.46 (pulled in transitively by
`mlflow-skinny`) as vulnerable to CWE-78 command injection via the
`upload_pack` / `receive_pack` kwargs on `Repo.clone_from`,
`Remote.fetch`, `Remote.pull`, `Remote.push`. GitPython's blocklist
runs before Python normalises `_` → `-`, so underscore-form kwargs
bypass the `allow_unsafe_options=False` guard. Affected range
`[3.1.30, 3.1.47)`; fix is 3.1.47+. The OntoBricks codebase does not
import `git` directly (no `from git import …` anywhere under `src/`),
so we are not exposed in our own paths, but the vulnerable wheel was
still in `uv.lock`.

Changes:

1. `pyproject.toml` — added `gitpython>=3.1.47` to
   `[tool.uv].constraint-dependencies` (next to the existing `mako` /
   `pygments` constraints) so the resolver is forced onto a patched
   build without making it a real direct dependency. Kept GitPython
   transitive via `mlflow-skinny`.

2. `uv.lock` — regenerated via `uv lock`; resolver bumped
   `gitpython 3.1.46 → 3.1.47`. No other packages moved. `numpy 2.4.0
   yanked` warning is unrelated and pre-existing.

Modified files:
- `pyproject.toml`
- `uv.lock`

Tests: `uv run pytest -q` → **1892 passed** in 63.9s.

Follow-up — second GitPython advisory covered by the same pin:
GHSA-x2qx-6953-8485 / CVE-2026-42284 ("Argument injection via
`multi_options` shlex.split bypass in `_clone()` / `Submodule.update`")
lists affected `<= 3.1.44`, patched `>= 3.1.47`. The constraint added
above already locks 3.1.47, so no further pyproject/lock change is
needed. We also have no code-path exposure: no `clone_from`,
`Repo.clone`, `Submodule.update`, or `multi_options` calls under
`src/` (the only matches for "Submodule" are docstring prose).
